{{DEFAULTSORT:Shamsuzzoha, Mohammad}} [[Category:1934 births]] [[Category:1969 deaths]] [[Category:Bangladeshi academics]] [[Category:University of Dhaka alumni]] [[Category:Alumni of Imperial College London]] [[Category:People from Bankura district]] [[Category:Causes and prelude of the Bangladesh Liberation War]] [[Category:Protest-related deaths]] {{Bangladesh-academic-bio-stub}}

{{Infobox song <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Songs --> | Name = Oxford Town | Cover = | Artist = [[Bob Dylan]] | Album = [[The Freewheelin' Bob Dylan]] | Released = May 27, 1963 | track_no = 9 | Recorded = December 6, 1962 | Genre = [[Folk music|Folk]] | Length = 1:50 | Writer = [[Bob Dylan]] | Label = [[Columbia Records]] | Tracks = {{The Freewheelin' Bob Dylan tracks}} }} "'''Oxford Town'''" is a song written by [[United States|American]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[Bob Dylan]] in 1962. It was recorded in [[CBS 30th Street Studio|Columbia]]'s Studio A on December 6, 1962 for his second album, ''[[The Freewheelin' Bob Dylan]]''.
The song was composed in response to an open invitation from ''[[Broadside (magazine)|Broadside]]'' magazine for songs about one of the top news events of 1962: the enrollment of a black student, [[James Meredith]], in the [[University of Mississippi]] on October 1.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Battle of Mississippi|publisher=[[Broadside (magazine)|Broadside]]''|url=http://www.broadsidemagazine.com/All/14.pdf|date=October 1962|accessdate=2010-12-13}}</ref> Among other submissions was [[Phil Ochs]]' song "Ballad of Oxford, Mississippi".<ref>{{cite web|first=Phil|last=Ochs|title=Ballad of Oxford, Mississippi|publisher=[[Broadside (magazine)|Broadside]]''|url=http://www.broadsidemagazine.com/All/14.pdf|date=November 1962|accessdate=2010-12-13}}</ref> The lyrics and music from Dylan's song were printed December 1962 in ''Broadside'''s issue #17.<ref>{{cite web|first=Bob|last=Dylan|title=Oxford Town|publisher=[[Broadside (magazine)|Broadside]]''|url=http://www.broadsidemagazine.com/All/17.pdf|date=December 1962|accessdate=2010-12-13}}</ref>
Except that the University of Mississippi is located in [[Oxford, Mississippi]], "Oxford Town" does not mention either Meredith or the university by name. Later, in an interview with [[Studs Terkel]], Dylan said, "It deals with the Meredith case, but then again it doesn't... I wrote that when it happened, and I could have written that yesterday. It's still the same. 'Somebody better investigate soon' that's a verse in the song."
Besides the ''Freewheelin''' release, Dylan recorded a version of "Oxford Town" for Broadside Sessions in November 1962. He also recorded a [[demo recording|demo]] of the song for his [[music publisher (popular music)|music publisher]] [[M. Witmark & Sons]] in March 1963. This version was released in October 2010 on ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 9 – The Witmark Demos: 1962–1964]]''.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.bobdylan.com/#/early-demos-and-mono-recordings | title=The Bootleg Series Volume 9—The Witmark Demos: 1962-1964 | publisher=bobdylan.com | accessdate=2010-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Olof|last=Bjorner|title=Still on the Road: Recording sessions & concerts, 1963|url=http://www.bjorner.com/still.htm#y63|accessdate=2010-12-13}}</ref>
==Other notable recordings== [[Richie Havens]] recorded "Oxford Town" in 1966 for his second album, ''Electric Havens''. [[Tim O'Brien (musician)|Tim O'Brien]] featured the song on his 1996 release of Dylan covers, ''[[Red on Blonde]]''. The alternative bluegrass band [[Crooked Still]] recorded the song for their 2006 album ''Shaken by a Low Sound''. [[Hugues Aufray]] released a French version of this (and ten other Dylan songs) in 1965 on his LP ''Aufray chante Dylan''. [[Pat Wictor]] recorded Oxford Town on his album ''Heaven is so High'' in 2006.
==See also== * [[African-American Civil Rights Movement (1954–68) in popular culture|African-American Civil Rights Movement in popular culture]]
